05319nam a22008295i 9780674726574DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20132013mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979904686  a97806747265747 a10.4159/harvard.97806747265742doi  a(DE-B1597)209643  a(OCoLC)861692024  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aHIS0200002bisacsh04a782.109200aOrpheus in the Marketplace :bJacopo Peri and the Economy of Late Renaissance Florence. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (479 p.) :b18 halftones, 19 line illustrations, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aI Tatti Studies in Italian Renaissance History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tPreface -- tA Note on Money -- tA Note on Transcriptions -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Social World -- t2. The Economic World -- t3. The Musical World -- t4. Last Years, Death, and the End of the Line -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tA. Chronology -- tB. Letters from Jacopo Peri -- tC. Catalogue of Peri’s musical works -- tD. Four poems concerning Jacopo Peri -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Florentine musician Jacopo Peri (1561-1633) is known as the composer of the first operas--they include the earliest to survive complete, Euridice (1600), in which Peri sang the role of Orpheus. The recent discovery of a large number of private account books belonging to him and his family allows for a greater exploration of Peri's professional and personal life. Richard Goldthwaite, an economic historian, and Tim Carter, a musicologist, have done more, however, than write a biography: their investigation exposes the value of such financial documents as a primary source for an entire period. This record of Peri's wide-ranging investments and activities in the marketplace enables the first detailed account of the Florentine economy in the late sixteenth and early seventeenth centuries, and opens a new perspective on one of Europe's principal centers of capitalism. His economic circumstances reflect continuities and transformations in Florentine society, and the strategies for negotiating them, under the Medici grand dukes. They also allow a reevaluation of Peri the singer and composer that elucidates the cultural life of a major artistic center even in changing times, providing a quite different view of what it meant to be a musician in late Renaissance Italy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aComposers -- Italy -- Biography. 0aComposers -- Italy -- Florence -- Economic conditions -- 16th century. 0aComposers -- Italy -- Florence -- Economic conditions -- 17th century. 0aFinance, Personal -- Italy -- Florence -- History -- 16th century. 0aFinance, Personal -- Italy -- Florence -- History -- 17th century. 0aPeri, Jacopo, -- 1561-1633 -- Finance, Personal. 0aPeri, Jacopo, -- 1561-1633. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2013z9783110317350oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ARTS AND ARCHITECTURE 2013z978311031715208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET KUNST UND ARCHITEKTUR 2013z9783110317145oZDB-23-DKA08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831104422050 cprintz978067472464840uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067472657440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674726574423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674726574/orig